<style|generic>

<\body>
  <doc-data|<doc-title|Proof Outline: Intertwining Operator between Chebyshev
  Type 1 Polynomials and its Orthogonalized Fourier
  Transforms>|<doc-author|<author-data|<author-name|Stephen Crowley>>>>

  <section|Introduction>

  Provide an overview of the proof and its significance.

  <section|Preliminaries>

  Define Chebyshev Type 1 polynomials and review properties of the Fourier
  transform.

  <section|Step 1: Fourier Transform of Chebyshev Type 1 Polynomials>

  Define the Fourier transform and apply it to Chebyshev Type 1 polynomials
  to obtain the sequence <math|Y>.

  <section|Step 2: Gram-Schmidt Process on <math|Y>>

  Apply the Gram-Schmidt process to the sequence <math|Y> to obtain an
  orthogonalized sequence <math|Z>.

  <section|Step 3: Constructing the Intertwining Operator>

  Define the intertwining operator <math|T:V\<rightarrow\>W>, where <math|V>
  is the space spanned by Chebyshev Type 1 polynomials and <math|W> is the
  space spanned by the orthogonalized Fourier transformed polynomials.

  <subsection|Property 1: Preservation of Inner Products>

  Show that <math|T> preserves inner products between vectors in <math|V> and
  <math|W>.

  <subsection|Property 2: Surjectivity>

  Prove that <math|T> is surjective, meaning every element in <math|W> is
  reachable from <math|V>.

  <section|Conclusion>

  Summarize the main results of the proof and discuss implications.
</body>

